Variables with a P value< .05 in the univariate analysis were entered into multivariate logistic regression analysis. Compared with parameters in patients with COVID-19, patients with H1N1 were more inclined to have productive cough (OR, 9.576; 95% CI, 1.729-64.711; P = .011), consolidation manifested on chest CT imaging (OR, 4.956; 95% CI, 1.518-16.176; P = .008), and higher SOFA scores (OR, 2.263; 95% CI, 1.124-3.574; P = .006). Furthermore, compared with additional parameters in patients with H1N1, patients with COVID-19 had a greater disposition to be older (OR, 0.908; 95% CI, 0.843-0.978; P = .011), exhibit symptoms of fatigue (OR, 0.117; 95% CI, 0.021-0.941]; P = .013), exhibit GI symptoms (OR, 0.100; 95% CI, 0.009-0.984; P = .044), and present with ground-glass opacities on chest CT scans (OR, 0.086; 95% CI, 0.015-0.490; P = .006) (Fig 2
, Table 5
).
